### The Bug

The problem is that the `Array.prototype.forEach()` method does not wait for promises. When you pass an `async` function to `forEach`, it fires off the promises but immediately moves on to the next iteration without waiting for them to resolve. Because of this, the code reaches the `console.log('total:', total)` line before any of the file reads have finished, which is why it prints `0`.

### The Fix

To fix this, you can use a standard `for...of` loop, which natively supports the `await` keyword and will execute sequentially. Alternatively, you can use `Promise.all()` to run the file reads concurrently and wait for all of them to finish.

Here is the corrected code using a `for...of` loop:

```js
const fs = require('fs/promises');

async function main(files) {
  let total = 0;
  for (const f of files) {
    const data = await fs.readFile(f, 'utf8');
    total += data.length;
  }
  console.log('total:', total);
}
```

If you want to process the files concurrently (which is much faster for I/O operations), you can use `Promise.all()` with `.map()`:

```js
const fs = require('fs/promises');

async function main(files) {
  // Read all files concurrently
  const dataArray = await Promise.all(
    files.map(f => fs.readFile(f, 'utf8'))
  );

  // Calculate total length after all files are read
  const total = dataArray.reduce((sum, data) => sum + data.length, 0);

  console.log('total:', total);
}
```

