}

class LruTtl {
  constructor(maxSize, defaultTtlMs = Infinity) {
    if (!Number.isInteger(maxSize) || maxSize < 1) {
      throw new TypeError('maxSize must be a positive integer');
    }
    this.maxSize = maxSize;
    this.defaultTtlMs = defaultTtlMs;

    // 1. Hash table: key -> Node
    this.map = new Map();

    // 2. Doubly-linked list: most-recent is just after head,
    //    least-recent is just before tail
    this.head = new Node(null, null);
    this.tail = new Node(null, null);
    this.head.next = this.tail;
    this.tail.prev = this.head;
  }

  // ---------- linked-list helpers (all O(1)) ----------

  _addFront(node) {
    node.prev = this.head;
    node.next = this.head.next;
    this.head.next.prev = node;
    this.head.next = node;
  }

  _remove(node) {
    node.prev.next = node.next;
    node.next.prev = node.prev;
    node.prev = null;
    node.next = null;
  }

  _moveToFront(node) {
    this._remove(node);
    this._addFront(node);
  }

  // ---------- public API ----------

  get(k) {
    const node = this.map.get(k);
    if (node === undefined) return undefined;

    // Lazy expiry: delete only when the entry is actually touched
    if (Number.isFinite(node.expiresAt) && Date.now() >= node.expiresAt) {
      this._remove(node);
      this.map.delete(k);
      return undefined;
    }

    this._moveToFront(node);
    return node.value;
  }

  set(k, v, ttlMs = this.defaultTtlMs) {
    // Non-positive / infinite TTL means "no expiry"
    let expiresAt = Infinity;
    if (ttlMs != null && Number.isFinite(ttlMs) && ttlMs > 0) {
      expiresAt = Date.now() + ttlMs;
    }

    const existing = this.map.get(k);
    if (existing !== undefined) {
      // Update in place and mark as most-recently used
      existing.value = v;
      existing.expiresAt = expiresAt;
      this._moveToFront(existing);
    } else {
      const node = new Node(k, v, expiresAt);
      this.map.set(k, node);
      this._addFront(node);

      // Evict the least-recently-used entry if we overflowed
      if (this.map.size > this.maxSize) {
        const lru = this.tail.prev;
        this.map.delete(lru.key);
        this._remove(lru);
      }
    }
    return this;
  }
}
```

### The key trick

The trick is to **store the same entry as one node object in two synchronized structures**:

1. A `Map` gives **O(1) lookup by key**.
2. A **doubly linked list** of those same node objects gives **O(1) LRU ordering**.

Because each node carries its own `prev` / `next` pointers, promoting an entry to the front or evicting the oldest entry only requires rewiring a constant number of pointers — no scanning, no sorting.

For the TTL part, the trick is to store an **absolute `expiresAt` timestamp** (`Date.now() + ttlMs`) instead of a countdown. Then `get()` only needs one comparison (`Date.now() >= expiresAt`) to decide lazy expiry, with no background timers, sweeps, or bookkeeping.

Resulting behavior:

- `get(k)` → O(1): map lookup, one expiry check, and optionally move-to-front.
- `set(k, v, ttlMs?)` → O(1): insert or update, rewire list pointers, and evict the tail if over capacity.
- Expired items are removed **lazily**, only when accessed after their deadline.

**Note on a simpler alternative:** A plain `Map` alone can also implement LRU by `delete`ing and re-`set`ting the key on every `get`, which is O(1) in modern JavaScript. The dual-structure version above is the classic constant-time design because it keeps ordering updates inside the linked list without touching the `Map` on every access, and it naturally gives each entry a stable object to hold TTL metadata.
